<exercisegroup cols="2">
	<title>Interpreting matrix equality as a system of equations</title>

	<introduction><p>
		In each case,
		determining the variable values that make the matrix equality true.
		In any equality where <m>\zerovec</m> appears,
		assume it represents a zero matrix of appropriate dimensions.
	</p></introduction>

	<exercise>
		<statement><p><m>\displaystyle
			\begin{bmatrix}
				b + 3 c \amp c + 3 b - 2 a \\
				a + 4 c \amp a - 4 b - 3 c
			\end{bmatrix}
			=
			\left[\begin{array}{rr}
				-5 \amp 3 \\
				-9 \amp 0
			\end{array}\right]
		</m></p></statement>
		<solution><p>
			Comparing corresponding entries on each side of the matrix equality leads to system of equations
			<me>
				\begin{sysofeqns}{rcrcrcr}
					     \amp   \amp   b \amp + \amp 3 c \amp = \amp -5 \\
					-2 a \amp + \amp 3 b \amp + \amp   c \amp = \amp  3 \\
					   a \amp   \amp     \amp + \amp 4 c \amp = \amp -9 \\
					   a \amp - \amp 4 b \amp - \amp 3 c \amp = \amp  0
				\end{sysofeqns}
			</me>.
			Turn this system into an augmented matrix and reduce:
			<me>
				\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r}
					 0 \amp  1 \amp  3 \amp -5 \\
					-2 \amp  3 \amp  1 \amp  3 \\
					 1 \amp  0 \amp  4 \amp -9 \\
					 2 \amp -4 \amp -3 \amp  0
				\end{array}\right]
				\longrightarrow
				\left(\begin{array}{rrr|r}
					1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
					0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp  1 \\
					0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
					0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp  0
				\end{array}\right)
			</me>.
			This system is consistent with one unique solution <m>a = -1</m>, <m>b = 1</m>, <m>c = -2</m>.
		</p></solution>
	</exercise>

	<!-- TODO lin.comb of two 3-dim vectors equals 3-dim vector -->
